<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
Thallus areolate, yellow-brown, orange-brown, often appears as greyish-brown, generally heavily pruinose, continuous, 5.7-10.0 cm across; areolae aggregated by 4-14 small areolae (often surrounded by black prothallus), small areolae up to 0.1 mm across, concave or flat, irregular, pruinose; margin pruinose; prothallus black, distinct. Upper cortex 32.0-50.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
thick, yellow-brown granules pigmented; epinecral layer 15.0-20.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
thick; algal layer 47.5-65.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
thick, cells 7.5-8.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in diam., ellipsoid. Apothecia frequent, crowded, immersed or isolated from areolae, 0.3-0.8 mm in diam.; disc black, concave to flat, aggregated, cracked once mature, thin pruinose; margin reduced, slightly raised. Exciple almost absent. Hymenium 100.0-138.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
thick, colourless; paraphyses ca. 2.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
wide, branched, anastomosing or not; epihymenium ca. 15.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
thick, brown; subhymenium ca. 55.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
thick, colourless; hypothecium pale brown to brown. Asci 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Koerber" authorityYear="1855" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Porpidiaceae" genus="Porpidia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Porpidia" order="Lecideales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Porpidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-type, cylindrical, eight-spored; ascospores 7.0-9.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.0-4.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, ellipsoid, halonate (sometimes not distinct). Conidiomata immersed, oblate, black, margin heavily pruinose; conidia 7.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, bacilliform.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="chemistry">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Chemistry.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Thallus K-, C-. Medulla I+ violet. Confluentic acid, planaic acid and/or 2'-O-methylmicophyllinic acid.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Ecology and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">In China, growing on granite at elevations of 4300-4500 m in the alpine zone. This species is known from Yunnan Province of China.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
The materials of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rambold &amp; Pietschm., in Rambold, Biblioth. Lichenol. 34: 240" authorityYear="1989" baseAuthorityName="Ach." class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Lecideaceae" genus="Immersaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Immersaria athroocarpa" order="Lecideales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="athroocarpa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Immersaria athroocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Shangri-La County of Yunnan Province are morphologically identical with the specimen 
<bibRefCitation author="Hertel, H" journalOrPublisher="Khumbu Himal, Ergebnisse des Forschungsunternehmens Nepal Himalaya" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" pagination="145 - 458" refId="B8" refString="Hertel, H, 1977. Gesteinsbewohnende Arten der Sammelgattung Lecidea (Lichenes) aus Zentral-, Ost- und Sudasien. Khumbu Himal, Ergebnisse des Forschungsunternehmens Nepal Himalaya 6: 145 - 458" title="Gesteinsbewohnende Arten der Sammelgattung Lecidea (Lichenes) aus Zentral-, Ost- und Sudasien." volume="6" year="1977">Hertel (1977)</bibRefCitation>
reported from the same locality, but differ from the lectotype in its aggregate areolae, the aggregate apothecia and the smaller size of ascospores (7.0-9.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.0-4.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
). Based on the phenotypic and phylogenetic results, the material from Shangri-La is treated as a new species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. M. Xie &amp; Lu L. Zhang" authorityYear="2022" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Lecideaceae" genus="Immersaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Immersaria shangrilaensis" order="Lecideales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="shangrilaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Immersaria shangrilaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is characterised by its large thallus, up to 10.0 cm in diam., the aggregate areolae and apothecia and the small size of ascospores.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
